---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="The Three-Part Plantar Fasciitis Protocol | Practical Podiatrist">
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-12 text-slate-300 relative z-10">
    <header class="mb-12 border-b border-white/10 pb-8">
      <span class="text-xs font-bold text-accent uppercase tracking-widest block mb-2">Advanced Treatment Guide</span>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold tracking-tight text-white mb-4">The Three-Part Plantar Fasciitis Protocol</h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-slate-400">A complete biomechanical roadmap: Protect the tissue, drain the fluid, and control the chemical inflammatory cycle.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="space-y-8 text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed">
      <p>Plantar fasciitis occurs where the thick band of connective tissue running along the bottom of your foot inserts onto the calcaneus (the heel bone). When arches lack support, the foot elongates, putting tension on this insertion point like the plantar fascia is trying to tear off the heel bone. Swelling builds under the heel during rest, causing sharp pain on your first morning steps.</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mt-8 border-l-4 border-teal-400 pl-3">Part 1: Protect the Inflamed Tissues</h2>
      <p>Structural offloading is required: an orthopedic boot, supportive stability shoes, or shoes paired with firm over-the-counter orthotics. Never walk barefoot on hard floors.</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mt-8 border-l-4 border-teal-400 pl-3">Part 2: Reduce the Inflammation Locally (The Sponge Analogy)</h2>
      <p>Swollen tissue behaves like a dense sponge. Deep manual massage is mandatory to clear trapped fluid before bearing weight. Use the Emergency Tiptoe Fallback to keep the fascia slack if you cannot massage first.</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mt-8 border-l-4 border-teal-400 pl-3">Part 3: Prevent the Inflammation From Returning</h2>
      <p>Manage the chemical loop using Tier 1 Topicals (Voltaren), Tier 2 Oral NSAIDs, Tier 3 Oral Steroids via your PCP, or Tier 4 Specialist Injectables.</p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
